1 Sec. 13. 1. A health care entity or collection agency shall
2 not report any information to a consumer reporting agency
3 regarding a medical debt. Any portion of a medical debt that is
4 reported to a consumer reporting agency in violation of this
5 section shall be void.
6 2. A health care entity shall include in any contract entered
7 into with a collection agency, whether located within or outside of
8 this State, for the purchase or collection of medical debt a
9 provision that:
10 (a) Prohibits the collection agency from reporting any portion
11 of the medical debt to a consumer reporting agency.
12 (b) Provides that any portion of the medical debt reported to a
13 consumer reporting agency is void.
14 (c) Prohibits the collection agency from engaging in any of the
15 actions prohibited by section 14 of this act.
16 3. Any contract for the purchase or collection of medical debt
17 that does not comply with the provisions of this section is void and
18 unenforceable.
19 Sec. 14. A health care entity or collection agency shall not
20 engage in any of the following actions to collect a medical debt:
21 1. Causing or threatening the arrest of a consumer,
22 including, without limitation, an arrest pursuant to NRS 31.470 to
23 31.730, inclusive;
24 2. Obtaining or threatening to obtain a lien against any real
25 property of a consumer which consists, in whole or in part, of the
26 primary residence of the consumer;
27 3. Foreclosing or threatening to foreclose on any real
28 property of a consumer which consists, in whole or in part, of the
29 primary residence of the consumer;
30 4. Garnishing or threatening to garnish the wages of a
31 consumer or any refund of federal income taxes due to a
32 consumer; or
33 5. Garnishing, attaching or seizing, or threatening to garnish,
34 attach or seize, a bank account of a consumer.
35 Sec. 15. 1. A health care entity or collection agency shall
36 not engage in any extraordinary collection action until at least 180
37 days after the first bill for a medical debt has been sent to a
38 consumer.
39 2. At least 30 days before taking any extraordinary collection
40 action to collect a medical debt, a health care entity or collection
41 agency shall provide to the consumer a notice:
42 (a) Identifying the extraordinary collection action that will be
43 initiated in order to obtain payment;
